<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-088-132 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 205 135</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 1 1991 n1273 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Industry must come clean and green. (time for the informationtechnology industry to clean up its act)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davidson, Clive.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information technology (IT) companies do damage to the environmenton a daily basis and are lax to take action for clean-up.andP;  Thereare no standards and few IT companies publish results ofenvironmental impact audits, audits that may have been conductedinternally by persons lacking in objectivity or experience in suchmatters.andP;  One firm, the Netherlands-based software house ofBSO/Origin has published a report that delineates a full set ofenvironmental accounts.andP;  The information is part of the company'sannual report, published in Apr 1991, and provides details on thecost of atmospheric emissions from heating sources, electricitygeneration sources, air travel, waste incineration and employeescars.andP;  Electronics and Computing for Peace (ECP) is a 250-memberorganization that operates special interest groups and publishes amonthly newsletter.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information SystemsWaste ManagementEnvironmental protectionComputer industryElectronics and Computing for Peace.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>